==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sell
<hw>Sell</hw> <pr>(s⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>selle</ets>, L. <ets>sella</ets>, akin to <ets>sedere</ets> to sit.
See <er>Sit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A saddle for a horse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He left his lofty steed with golden <qex>self</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A throne or lofty seat.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sell
<hw>Sell</hw> <pr>(s⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sold</conjf> <pr>(s⟦omac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Selling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sellen</ets>,
<ets>sillen</ets>, AS. <ets>sellan</ets>, <ets>syllan</ets>, to give, to
deliver; akin to OS. <ets>sellian</ets>, OFries. <ets>sella</ets>, OHG.
<ets>sellen</ets>, Icel. <ets>selja</ets> to hand over, to sell, Sw.
<ets>s⟦aum⟧lja</ets> to sell, Dan. <ets>s⟦ae⟧lge</ets>, Goth.
<ets>saljan</ets> to offer a sacrifice; all from a noun akin to E.
<ets>sale</ets>. Cf. <er>Sale</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To transfer
to another for an equivalent; to give up for a valuable consideration;
to dispose of in return for something, especially for money. It is the
correlative of <inv>buy</inv>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou wilt be perfect, go and <qex>sell</qex> that thou hast,
and give to the poor.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xix. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am changed; I'll go <qex>sell</qex> all my land.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sell</xex> is corellative to <xex>buy</xex>, as one
party <xex>buys</xex> what the other <xex>sells</xex>. It is
distinguished usually from <xex>exchange</xex> or <xex>barter</xex>, in
which one commodity is given for another; whereas in <xex>selling</xex>
the consideration is usually money, or its representative in current
notes.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a matter of bargain and sale of; to accept a
price or reward for, as for a breach of duty, trust, or the like; to
betray.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You would have <qex>sold</qex> your king to slaughter.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To impose upon; to trick; to deceive; to make a fool
of; to cheat.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sell one's life dearly</b></col>, <cd>to cause much
loss to those who take one's life, as by killing a number of one's
assailants.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To sell</b></col> (anything)
<col><b>out</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to dispose of it wholly or entirely;
as, he had <xex>sold out</xex> his corn, or his interest in a
business.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sell</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Sell
<hw>Sell</hw> <pr>(s⟦ecr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
practice selling commodities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will buy with you, <qex>sell</qex> with you; . . . but I will
not eat with you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be sold; <as>as, corn <ex>sells</ex> at a good
price</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sell out</b></col>, <cd>to sell one's whole stock in
trade or one's entire interest in a property or a
business.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sell</ent>⟦br⟧

